WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.850 --> 00:00:03.970
&gt;&gt; Narrator: From the Library
of Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:22.410 --> 00:00:24.680
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: So my name
is Stephen Winick and I'm here

00:00:24.680 --> 00:00:28.260
at the Library of Congress,
where I'm the writer and editor

00:00:28.260 --> 00:00:29.860
for the American Folklife Center.

00:00:29.860 --> 00:00:31.910
And I'm here with the three members

00:00:31.910 --> 00:00:35.210
of the group NOKA,
and with Mikel Markez.

00:00:35.210 --> 00:00:37.290
And we're going to
talk about Basque music

00:00:37.290 --> 00:00:39.550
and culture, and about their group.

00:00:39.550 --> 00:00:42.980
So I'm going to address some
general questions in English,

00:00:42.980 --> 00:00:45.160
and any of you can answer.

00:00:45.160 --> 00:00:48.280
And I also have some questions
in French that I'll ask later

00:00:48.280 --> 00:00:49.740
for Mikel specifically --

00:00:49.740 --> 00:00:51.040
&gt;&gt; Mikel Markez: Okay.

00:00:51.040 --> 00:00:52.760
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: About the
Basque country and life there.

00:00:52.760 --> 00:00:57.180
But for now, you are
three Basque-Americans,

00:00:57.180 --> 00:01:01.190
and perform Basque
language songs and music.

00:01:01.190 --> 00:01:03.070
So let's talk a little
about the Basque culture,

00:01:03.070 --> 00:01:07.970
and if you could just start out
by telling us what, you know,

00:01:07.970 --> 00:01:11.640
Americans need to know about
Basque culture to understand

00:01:11.640 --> 00:01:16.530
who are the Basques, and what's
their language and culture like?

00:01:16.530 --> 00:01:20.430
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: Well, the
Basque country is a translation

00:01:20.430 --> 00:01:22.310
from the English of Euskal
Herria, which were the first two

00:01:22.310 --> 00:01:25.370
of the seven provinces, where the
language, Basque has been spoken.

00:01:25.370 --> 00:01:27.870
So there are -- right now it's
divided into seven provinces.

00:01:27.870 --> 00:01:31.640
Four which are in Spain and
three of which are in France.

00:01:31.640 --> 00:01:34.450
But there's a language there
that is spoken that is unrelated

00:01:34.450 --> 00:01:37.330
to any other language in the
world, so it's an isolate --

00:01:37.330 --> 00:01:39.240
so it's not related to Spanish
or French, or anything else.

00:01:39.240 --> 00:01:41.900 position:56%
So in America what they should know,
is it's a great secret language.

00:01:41.900 --> 00:01:43.240
So everyone should learn
it -- not everybody --

00:01:43.240 --> 00:01:44.540
enough people should
learn it so they can talk

00:01:44.540 --> 00:01:47.140
about other people while
they're in America.

00:01:47.140 --> 00:01:52.010
And so we are -- the three of us
are daughters, or granddaughters

00:01:52.010 --> 00:01:54.090
of immigrants who came
from the Basque country.

00:01:54.090 --> 00:01:57.280
From -- my family's from the
southern side, so the northwest

00:01:57.280 --> 00:02:00.440
of France, and Nafarroa
[Beherea] is the province,

00:02:00.440 --> 00:02:01.740
about five miles from
the French border.

00:02:01.740 --> 00:02:05.950
So my parents came from
there to work in the states.

00:02:05.950 --> 00:02:08.710
And Cathy and Andrea can speak
to their own family histories.

00:02:08.710 --> 00:02:10.150
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans: My
parents were born in California;

00:02:10.150 --> 00:02:12.970
it's my grandfathers
that immigrated to --

00:02:12.970 --> 00:02:15.350
one to Chino and one
to northern California.

00:02:15.350 --> 00:02:16.650
They married Basque-American women,

00:02:16.650 --> 00:02:18.750
so my grandmothers were
also born in California.

00:02:18.750 --> 00:02:21.300
They came from the French
side of the Basque country.

00:02:21.300 --> 00:02:22.720
&gt;&gt; Andréa Bidart: Yeah,
my parents also were born

00:02:22.720 --> 00:02:24.020
in the French side of
the Basque country.

00:02:24.020 --> 00:02:26.870
My mom's from Alsace, and my
father's from St. Estevan.

00:02:26.870 --> 00:02:31.870
And my father immigrated as
a shepherd in the mid-50s,

00:02:31.870 --> 00:02:34.060
and then he got into
the dairy business.

00:02:34.060 --> 00:02:39.570
And went back to marry my mom after
seven years, and that's my history.

00:02:39.570 --> 00:02:40.870
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Great.

00:02:40.870 --> 00:02:44.260
Well you know, I think if Americans
know about Basque Americans at all,

00:02:44.260 --> 00:02:47.020
they tend to associate
them, I think, with Idaho

00:02:47.020 --> 00:02:48.330
and possibly with Nevada.

00:02:48.330 --> 00:02:50.770
I'm not sure that a
lot of Americans know

00:02:50.770 --> 00:02:54.390
that there's Basque
folks in California.

00:02:54.390 --> 00:02:58.480
So are the Basques in
the West generally aware

00:02:58.480 --> 00:03:01.230
of one another's communities
as well as the other states?

00:03:01.230 --> 00:03:02.710 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans: Yes, we have --

00:03:02.710 --> 00:03:05.930 position:56%
in California the biggest Basque
clubs are in Chino where we're from.

00:03:05.930 --> 00:03:08.470
There's one in Bakersfield
and San Francisco.

00:03:08.470 --> 00:03:11.000
And those are ones that each
have their own clubhouse.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:14.890 position:56%
So yes, we do know each other very
well; we go to each other's picnics.

00:03:14.890 --> 00:03:17.820
There's -- well the picnics for
the children, the kids get together

00:03:17.820 --> 00:03:20.950
and learn dances together
and songs together, but yes,

00:03:20.950 --> 00:03:22.250
we know each other very well.

00:03:22.250 --> 00:03:23.550
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Mm-hm.

00:03:23.550 --> 00:03:24.850
&gt;&gt; Andréa Bidart: And
it's also connected

00:03:24.850 --> 00:03:26.150
through the North American
Basque Organization.

00:03:26.150 --> 00:03:28.760
And there are like triannual
meetings, and communication.

00:03:28.760 --> 00:03:30.610
We have a website, so --

00:03:30.610 --> 00:03:31.910
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Mm-hm.

00:03:31.910 --> 00:03:35.790
So what kind of Basque cultural
outlets are there in California?

00:03:35.790 --> 00:03:39.360
You mentioned the clubs,
are there other sort of ways

00:03:39.360 --> 00:03:40.870 position:56%
in which Basques get together and --

00:03:40.870 --> 00:03:42.170
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: Sure --

00:03:42.170 --> 00:03:43.470
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: And
perform their culture?

00:03:43.470 --> 00:03:44.770
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria:
So in addition to --

00:03:44.770 --> 00:03:46.070
we call them Basque picnics.

00:03:46.070 --> 00:03:47.370
So they're big -- they
are pretty big festivals.

00:03:47.370 --> 00:03:49.950
So the Basque community will
have Basque picnics in --

00:03:49.950 --> 00:03:51.290
every year at the same time.

00:03:51.290 --> 00:03:52.590
So the Basque picnics

00:03:52.590 --> 00:03:55.240
and the different communities
will go to each other's picnics.

00:03:55.240 --> 00:03:56.680
So we tend to go to the
ones in Bakersfield;

00:03:56.680 --> 00:03:58.290
they'll come to our picnics.

00:03:58.290 --> 00:04:00.500 position:56%
And then depending on the community,

00:04:00.500 --> 00:04:02.910
but we have an actual clubhouse
-- a Chino Basque club.

00:04:02.910 --> 00:04:04.410
So we actually have
monthly gatherings,

00:04:04.410 --> 00:04:05.710
and we'll have lunches or dinners.

00:04:05.710 --> 00:04:08.650 position:56%
And we'll have -- we've brought
people over from the Basque Country,

00:04:08.650 --> 00:04:10.880
like Mikel's been there
before with other singers.

00:04:10.880 --> 00:04:12.180 position:56%
And we've brought over Kepa Junkera.

00:04:12.180 --> 00:04:16.320
[Inaudible] has been there; we've
had dance groups perform there.

00:04:16.320 --> 00:04:17.790
But even when we don't
have entertainment

00:04:17.790 --> 00:04:19.250
from the Basque Country,
we'll get together

00:04:19.250 --> 00:04:22.110
and have a meal that's
prepared by Basque-Americans

00:04:22.110 --> 00:04:25.400
or Basque immigrants, and just
to spend some time together.

00:04:25.400 --> 00:04:26.740
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans: There are
also some Basque restaurants.

00:04:26.740 --> 00:04:28.040
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: Yeah,
Basque restaurants, sure.

00:04:28.040 --> 00:04:29.340
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans: In
Chino we only have one.

00:04:29.340 --> 00:04:31.130
Now Bakersfield has I
don't know, maybe four

00:04:31.130 --> 00:04:32.430
or five Basque restaurants.

00:04:32.430 --> 00:04:34.650
San Francisco has one as well.

00:04:34.650 --> 00:04:38.820 position:56%
And back in the day, I mean in Chino
it was where all the shepherds came.

00:04:38.820 --> 00:04:42.100
They were boarders there, so the
owners -- the woman, Monique,

00:04:42.100 --> 00:04:44.800
she would cook for all of the
shepherds; that's where they lived.

00:04:44.800 --> 00:04:47.640
Andréa Bidart: And it's organized
into communities, and you --

00:04:47.640 --> 00:04:50.040
each community has usually
its own dance group.

00:04:50.040 --> 00:04:52.340
So we have like three
Basque dance groups.

00:04:52.340 --> 00:04:55.170
To the littlest ones, and
then the older ones and on up.

00:04:55.170 --> 00:04:57.460
And then we have the
sport too, pilota.

00:04:57.460 --> 00:05:02.090
Like in Chino we have the young
ones learning how to do pilota.

00:05:02.090 --> 00:05:03.880
And there's a lot of
card game going on.

00:05:03.880 --> 00:05:06.220
Mouche is the standard card game.

00:05:06.220 --> 00:05:08.550
I know my mother plays
at least twice a week.

00:05:08.550 --> 00:05:10.490
And then each club
has its competition,

00:05:10.490 --> 00:05:12.190
and then there's the
national competition.

00:05:12.190 --> 00:05:15.060
And it goes international
competition, so --

00:05:15.060 --> 00:05:16.360
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Wow.

00:05:16.360 --> 00:05:17.660
&gt;&gt; Andréa Bidart: So yeah.

00:05:17.660 --> 00:05:18.960
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans:
It's pretty organized.

00:05:18.960 --> 00:05:20.260
&gt;&gt; Andréa Bidart: It
is pretty organized.

00:05:20.260 --> 00:05:21.560
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Yeah, wow.

00:05:21.560 --> 00:05:22.860
So in terms of song, I mean
you guys ended up as --

00:05:22.860 --> 00:05:24.830
with song as sort of your
primary expression of your --

00:05:24.830 --> 00:05:26.130
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans: Right.

00:05:26.130 --> 00:05:27.430
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Basque identity.

00:05:27.430 --> 00:05:31.610
So is that an important part of
Basque life in California as well?

00:05:31.610 --> 00:05:32.910
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: Sure.

00:05:32.910 --> 00:05:34.980
I mean I think that one of the
main things the Basque movement has

00:05:34.980 --> 00:05:36.700
brought I think was
the love of song.

00:05:36.700 --> 00:05:38.440
And there's an old -- I think
it's a French saying that

00:05:38.440 --> 00:05:40.100
"The Basques are the
people who sing".

00:05:40.100 --> 00:05:41.420
I've heard that before.

00:05:41.420 --> 00:05:44.200
And Basques usually do know how
to sing, and it's a tradition

00:05:44.200 --> 00:05:45.500
in the Basque-American communities.

00:05:45.500 --> 00:05:47.130
This is true both in the
California world where we're used

00:05:47.130 --> 00:05:49.040
to seeing, you know, Basque people.

00:05:49.040 --> 00:05:51.650
But even in Idaho or other
places, where after dinner --

00:05:51.650 --> 00:05:53.440
after any meal really,
there's those long tables

00:05:53.440 --> 00:05:54.880
and people will sit
around and sing songs.

00:05:54.880 --> 00:05:58.670 position:56%
So All of us grew up I think
hearing Basque song around the table

00:05:58.670 --> 00:06:00.390
at Basque restaurants or
picnics or in our homes --

00:06:00.390 --> 00:06:01.690
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans: Our
fathers sing together.

00:06:01.690 --> 00:06:02.990
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: Yeah,
all of our fathers sing.

00:06:02.990 --> 00:06:04.290
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans: Yeah.

00:06:04.290 --> 00:06:05.590
Yeah, so --

00:06:05.590 --> 00:06:06.890
&gt;&gt; Andréa Bidart: But
also song in church.

00:06:06.890 --> 00:06:08.190
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: Yeah.

00:06:08.190 --> 00:06:09.490
Mm-hm.

00:06:09.490 --> 00:06:10.790 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Andréa Bidart: Basques are
usually Catholic, and so we all grew

00:06:10.790 --> 00:06:12.090
up singing the church songs.

00:06:12.090 --> 00:06:13.990
And then song comes into --
there's a Basque camp for children,

00:06:13.990 --> 00:06:15.850
and they learn all
the different things.

00:06:15.850 --> 00:06:22.260
And Noka as a group has gone
to Udaleku and taught songs

00:06:22.260 --> 00:06:24.620
that would teach the
language to the children.

00:06:24.620 --> 00:06:25.920
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Mm-hm.

00:06:25.920 --> 00:06:27.220
&gt;&gt; Andréa Bidart: Through song.

00:06:27.220 --> 00:06:28.520
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Right.

00:06:28.520 --> 00:06:29.820
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans: And in those
masses, when people pass away,

00:06:29.820 --> 00:06:31.120
they call on NOKA to
do those Basque songs.

00:06:31.120 --> 00:06:32.420
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Right.

00:06:32.420 --> 00:06:33.720
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans: You know, two
of us can do it, because Cathy's

00:06:33.720 --> 00:06:35.020
in Pennsylvania, or any form
of us we can kind of help out.

00:06:35.020 --> 00:06:36.320
&gt;&gt; Andréa Bidart: But
we've sung at many --

00:06:36.320 --> 00:06:37.620
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans:
In that fashion too.

00:06:37.620 --> 00:06:38.920
&gt;&gt; Andréa Bidart: Many funerals.

00:06:38.920 --> 00:06:40.220
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans: Right.

00:06:40.220 --> 00:06:41.520
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Mm-hm.

00:06:41.520 --> 00:06:42.820
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans:
Weddings too [laughs].

00:06:42.820 --> 00:06:44.120
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria:
Yes, every now and again.

00:06:44.120 --> 00:06:45.420
&gt;&gt; Andréa Bidart: Some baptisms.

00:06:45.420 --> 00:06:46.720
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: So --
sure, so are there a lot

00:06:46.720 --> 00:06:48.020
of traditional Basque
songs in oral tradition

00:06:48.020 --> 00:06:49.320
in California would you say?

00:06:49.320 --> 00:06:50.620
Or -- ?

00:06:50.620 --> 00:06:51.920
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: I
would say most of them are.

00:06:51.920 --> 00:06:53.220
I mean I think that we're
one of the few groups --

00:06:53.220 --> 00:06:54.520
we might be the only group
in California, actually,

00:06:54.520 --> 00:06:56.980 position:56%
that is writing our own music -- our
own songs, and trying to find songs

00:06:56.980 --> 00:06:58.280
that are less traditional.

00:06:58.280 --> 00:07:00.970
So the songs -- we love
those songs, or if we have --

00:07:00.970 --> 00:07:05.100
our CD with Mikel is our third
CD, but the first two we did --

00:07:05.100 --> 00:07:06.400
the first one was really --

00:07:06.400 --> 00:07:07.700
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans:
All traditional songs.

00:07:07.700 --> 00:07:09.000
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: Here are
songs we heard up, you know --

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:10.300
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans: Yeah.

00:07:10.300 --> 00:07:11.600
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: -- singing
and learning, and so they're --

00:07:11.600 --> 00:07:13.340
and so those songs are
really the -- kind of the --

00:07:13.340 --> 00:07:15.400
and I think it's pretty typical
of immigrant communities,

00:07:15.400 --> 00:07:17.580
but you know, missing the homeland.

00:07:17.580 --> 00:07:19.350
And seeing their mother and
seeing their sweetheart,

00:07:19.350 --> 00:07:21.190
and wanting a sweetheart, and
those kind of heartbreaking songs.

00:07:21.190 --> 00:07:22.490
And we love those.

00:07:22.490 --> 00:07:23.790
So a lot of ballads.

00:07:23.790 --> 00:07:25.680
So I would say the norm is to --

00:07:25.680 --> 00:07:26.980
you know, people have books

00:07:26.980 --> 00:07:29.050
where they memorize them
to sing those songs.

00:07:29.050 --> 00:07:32.200
And we're trying to do a little bit
-- we do that too, but we're trying

00:07:32.200 --> 00:07:35.960
to kind of bring into more
public view the kind of songs

00:07:35.960 --> 00:07:38.480
that people don't generally sing.

00:07:38.480 --> 00:07:39.780
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick:
And when you say that,

00:07:39.780 --> 00:07:41.080
what kind of songs would that be?

00:07:41.080 --> 00:07:43.280 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: Well, I
would say that there are a few songs

00:07:43.280 --> 00:07:48.150
that I personally grew up
hearing that were where the women

00:07:48.150 --> 00:07:49.450
or girls were protagonists.

00:07:49.450 --> 00:07:50.820
I mean they're sort
of the object of --

00:07:50.820 --> 00:07:53.660 position:56%
like maybe a man want to marry them,
or they miss them, or the girls --

00:07:53.660 --> 00:07:57.190
that someone's telling them what to
do, but they don't have much say.

00:07:57.190 --> 00:07:59.970
And -- but we've really, in the
archives, have found a lot of songs

00:07:59.970 --> 00:08:02.910
that are -- like in today's
concert -- that are --

00:08:02.910 --> 00:08:05.590
and very often bad things
are happening to them.

00:08:05.590 --> 00:08:07.110
But women's stories;
a woman struggling.

00:08:07.110 --> 00:08:08.560
Or a woman who's a saint.

00:08:08.560 --> 00:08:11.170
Or a woman who has to go
someplace to, you know, find work

00:08:11.170 --> 00:08:12.780
and then gets in trouble.

00:08:12.780 --> 00:08:14.980
Or two sisters fighting.

00:08:14.980 --> 00:08:17.460
And we don't have, you know,
the bickering over a boy.

00:08:17.460 --> 00:08:18.950
So we're trying to really find --

00:08:18.950 --> 00:08:23.570
uncover and write songs that
about sort of putting women more

00:08:23.570 --> 00:08:26.230
in the forefront and not just in
the secondary or supporting roles,

00:08:26.230 --> 00:08:27.610
and sort of what men
want them to be.

00:08:27.610 --> 00:08:29.510
But kind of having
their own opinions

00:08:29.510 --> 00:08:30.810
about what they want to do or be.

00:08:30.810 --> 00:08:32.110
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Mm-hm.

00:08:32.110 --> 00:08:33.410
Great, that's really, you know,

00:08:33.410 --> 00:08:36.330
I think a really interesting
approach to song --

00:08:36.330 --> 00:08:37.630
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: Mm-hm.

00:08:37.630 --> 00:08:38.930
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick:
Especially from a group

00:08:38.930 --> 00:08:40.230
that got its start doing
traditional songs --

00:08:40.230 --> 00:08:41.530
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: Right.

00:08:41.530 --> 00:08:42.830
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick:
Because of that --

00:08:42.830 --> 00:08:44.130
you know, the sort of gender roles.

00:08:44.130 --> 00:08:45.430 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: And then we
also see our fathers, I mean they --

00:08:45.430 --> 00:08:46.730
Cathy, her mother sings about --

00:08:46.730 --> 00:08:48.030
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans: Right.

00:08:48.030 --> 00:08:49.330
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Right.

00:08:49.330 --> 00:08:50.630 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: We learned it
from our fathers and grandfathers --

00:08:50.630 --> 00:08:51.930
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans: And
my grandfather would sing

00:08:51.930 --> 00:08:53.230
around the table all
the time, so for --

00:08:53.230 --> 00:08:54.530
I think it was a very positive
thing is what it was to be Basque;

00:08:54.530 --> 00:08:55.830
to sing songs around the table.

00:08:55.830 --> 00:08:57.130
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Right.

00:08:57.130 --> 00:08:58.430
And so explain the connection
of that focus on women's stories

00:08:58.430 --> 00:09:00.280
with the -- the name, NOKA.

00:09:00.280 --> 00:09:02.320
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: Well,
if you insist [laughs].

00:09:02.320 --> 00:09:04.260
So NOKA is the name of our group,

00:09:04.260 --> 00:09:06.430
and we named ourselves
after a pronoun.

00:09:06.430 --> 00:09:09.140
Because in Basque there is no
he or she or "la" or "elle".

00:09:09.140 --> 00:09:11.910
The only place where there's gender
marking is in the familiar form.

00:09:11.910 --> 00:09:14.060
And there's one form of how
we're speaking to Mikel,

00:09:14.060 --> 00:09:15.360
called "Toka" [phonetic].

00:09:15.360 --> 00:09:17.080
Or if I'm speaking to Cathy
or Andrea, it's called "Noka".

00:09:17.080 --> 00:09:21.540
So it's to one female
addressee or a girl or a woman.

00:09:21.540 --> 00:09:25.660
And it really marks a relationship
of a familiarity or solidarity.

00:09:25.660 --> 00:09:27.290
But as you've seen in
the concert what ends

00:09:27.290 --> 00:09:31.260
up happening is it's used
not for sort of positive

00:09:31.260 --> 00:09:34.050
or friendship purposes, but
for telling a girl what to do,

00:09:34.050 --> 00:09:39.910
or to address to women who are
not necessarily looked well upon.

00:09:39.910 --> 00:09:43.040
So we thought that was
really interesting,

00:09:43.040 --> 00:09:44.740
and then that it's dying.

00:09:44.740 --> 00:09:47.920
So it's equivalent to the male
form, Toka, but it's not used

00:09:47.920 --> 00:09:49.620
in nearly sort of the context.

00:09:49.620 --> 00:09:51.950
And the Toka form; the male form,
has these positive association

00:09:51.950 --> 00:09:53.890
with this rugged, you know
[foreign language spoken],

00:09:53.890 --> 00:09:55.190
the eye candy, right?

00:09:55.190 --> 00:09:58.200
Like they're really sexy
and masculine, and you know.

00:09:58.200 --> 00:10:00.110
