they had in common was Basque.

00:24:45.480 --> 00:24:46.780
Which is very interesting.

00:24:46.780 --> 00:24:48.080
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: That
is very interesting, yeah.

00:24:48.080 --> 00:24:49.380
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: Yeah.

00:24:49.380 --> 00:24:50.680
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans:
I've known people

00:24:50.680 --> 00:24:51.980
to actually learn Basque in Chino.

00:24:51.980 --> 00:24:53.280
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: Yeah.

00:24:53.280 --> 00:24:54.580
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans: And from the
Spanish side they weren't able

00:24:54.580 --> 00:24:55.880
to speak Basque --

00:24:55.880 --> 00:24:57.180
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Mm-hm.

00:24:57.180 --> 00:24:58.480
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans:
During the time of Franco.

00:24:58.480 --> 00:24:59.780
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: Yeah.

00:24:59.780 --> 00:25:01.080
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans: And
they came to California

00:25:01.080 --> 00:25:02.380
and they learned it,
so it's [laughs].

00:25:02.380 --> 00:25:03.680
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick:
That's great [laughs].

00:25:03.680 --> 00:25:04.980
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans:
There are cases like that.

00:25:04.980 --> 00:25:06.280
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Yeah.

00:25:06.280 --> 00:25:07.580
So how is the language culture of
Basque doing, both in California

00:25:07.580 --> 00:25:08.880
and back in the home country?

00:25:08.880 --> 00:25:10.180
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria:
Well, I mean it's --

00:25:10.180 --> 00:25:12.820
there have been efforts
on -- mostly on --

00:25:12.820 --> 00:25:14.450
in three of the four
provinces on the Spanish side,

00:25:14.450 --> 00:25:15.750
and Mikel can speak to that --

00:25:15.750 --> 00:25:17.050
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Mm-hm.

00:25:17.050 --> 00:25:18.350
Sure.

00:25:18.350 --> 00:25:19.650
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria:
Since 1982 I think, where --

00:25:19.650 --> 00:25:20.950
after Franco died [laughs] --

00:25:20.950 --> 00:25:22.250
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Right.

00:25:22.250 --> 00:25:23.550
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria:
And Democracy came back.

00:25:23.550 --> 00:25:24.850
So had to wait a long
time for that to happen.

00:25:24.850 --> 00:25:27.120 position:56%
So even under Franco's regime, there
were clandestine Basque schools.

00:25:27.120 --> 00:25:30.630
And then once he died in 1975
-- after a very long time --

00:25:30.630 --> 00:25:32.650
and Democracy returned, there --

00:25:32.650 --> 00:25:35.540 position:56%
some communities were allowed to
use their language in the schools --

00:25:35.540 --> 00:25:37.300
in public -- for free,
for public schools.

00:25:37.300 --> 00:25:40.180
So that's helped a lot in
parts of the Basque country,

00:25:40.180 --> 00:25:43.740 position:56%
because you know, for the first time
-- for first time in a long time,

00:25:43.740 --> 00:25:45.710
people could speak it publicly
and there was support for that.

00:25:45.710 --> 00:25:49.150
So if you wanted to send your
child to a Basque school for free,

00:25:49.150 --> 00:25:50.820
you could do that from
the age three on.

00:25:50.820 --> 00:25:53.610
So there's a lot more people who
can speak Basque in those regions

00:25:53.610 --> 00:25:55.880
than previously, so I think --
I've heard anywhere between --

00:25:55.880 --> 00:25:57.860
like the total number
of between 750,000

00:25:57.860 --> 00:25:59.160
to a million people worldwide.

00:25:59.160 --> 00:26:00.460
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Mm-hm.

00:26:00.460 --> 00:26:01.760
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: So
that sounds pretty good.

00:26:01.760 --> 00:26:03.060
And it's better than it was,
but the problem is, you know,

00:26:03.060 --> 00:26:05.310
we're not out of the woods
yet, because most people

00:26:05.310 --> 00:26:07.420
who speak Basque speak
something else most of the time.

00:26:07.420 --> 00:26:08.720
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Right.

00:26:08.720 --> 00:26:10.020
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria:
They speak Spanish or --

00:26:10.020 --> 00:26:11.320
mostly Spanish or French.

00:26:11.320 --> 00:26:12.620
It's not taught so much
in the homes anymore.

00:26:12.620 --> 00:26:13.920
The people are learning
it at school.

00:26:13.920 --> 00:26:15.220
And we know how that is to
learn a language at school,

00:26:15.220 --> 00:26:16.520
you're like, eh, what is this for?

00:26:16.520 --> 00:26:17.820
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Mm-hm.

00:26:17.820 --> 00:26:19.120
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: And so
there's still a lot of issues

00:26:19.120 --> 00:26:21.710
with the language in terms
of -- I mean it's still --

00:26:21.710 --> 00:26:23.920
it's better institutionally than it
was, but it's still not as strong

00:26:23.920 --> 00:26:27.280 position:56%
as Spanish and French in terms of
where it is located institutionally.

00:26:27.280 --> 00:26:29.700
So -- so there's that.

00:26:29.700 --> 00:26:32.510
And in the -- in Basque-America,
I mean I think we're typical

00:26:32.510 --> 00:26:36.770
of other immigrant communities
where, you know, maybe I would say,

00:26:36.770 --> 00:26:39.520
perhaps of Cathy and
our generation --

00:26:39.520 --> 00:26:40.910
the daughters and sons
of immigrants,

00:26:40.910 --> 00:26:42.450
maybe 1 in 3 learned Basque?

00:26:42.450 --> 00:26:43.750
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Mm-hm.

00:26:43.750 --> 00:26:45.050
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria:
You know, which is --

00:26:45.050 --> 00:26:46.350 position:56%
you know, so I'm one of those three.

00:26:46.350 --> 00:26:47.650
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Right.

00:26:47.650 --> 00:26:48.950
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: But that was
just because who my parents were.

00:26:48.950 --> 00:26:50.250
But by the second generation, it's
-- very, very few people know it.

00:26:50.250 --> 00:26:51.550
Because by that point
-- so if it's people

00:26:51.550 --> 00:26:53.390
of my generation, English
is still better.

00:26:53.390 --> 00:26:56.100
And then, you know, even if
both speak Basque and English,

00:26:56.100 --> 00:26:57.400
English is their language together.

00:26:57.400 --> 00:26:58.700
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Mm-hm.

00:26:58.700 --> 00:27:00.000
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: Just
like in the -- so that's --

00:27:00.000 --> 00:27:02.080 position:56%
their normal language is English,
and then their language of education

00:27:02.080 --> 00:27:03.380
and profession is English.

00:27:03.380 --> 00:27:07.230 position:56%
And it's -- there aren't schools, so
it's possible, but it's difficult.

00:27:07.230 --> 00:27:08.940
I think people have a lot of
affection for the language,

00:27:08.940 --> 00:27:11.020
and they like to sing along to
words that they may not even know.

00:27:11.020 --> 00:27:13.850
But there's not been institutional
support that you would have

00:27:13.850 --> 00:27:16.580
in some other languages I think.

00:27:16.580 --> 00:27:18.370
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: So I guess
you guys have a mission [laughs].

00:27:18.370 --> 00:27:19.670
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: We do.

00:27:19.670 --> 00:27:20.970
&gt;&gt; Andréa Bidart: We do.

00:27:20.970 --> 00:27:22.270 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans: Got work to do.

00:27:22.270 --> 00:27:23.570
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: That's great.

00:27:23.570 --> 00:27:24.870
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: We do -- and
a lot of what we've been working

00:27:24.870 --> 00:27:26.490
on too is just -- just I think we
have to give ourselves a break.

00:27:26.490 --> 00:27:30.820
You know, the best way to be a
Basque speaker in California is

00:27:30.820 --> 00:27:32.120
to be born to my parents [laughs].

00:27:32.120 --> 00:27:33.420
Because it has nothing to do

00:27:33.420 --> 00:27:35.680 position:56%
with me [laughs] it was a completely
normal thing for them to do.

00:27:35.680 --> 00:27:38.520
So I think often people get blamed
for not passing on a language --

00:27:38.520 --> 00:27:39.820
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Right.

00:27:39.820 --> 00:27:41.120
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: Even though
there were good reasons for it.

00:27:41.120 --> 00:27:43.690
They were told not to, or it was
illegal or dangerous, or both.

00:27:43.690 --> 00:27:46.630
And I think -- and then sometimes
later on people are like,

00:27:46.630 --> 00:27:47.930
"Oh why didn't you
teach me this language?"

00:27:47.930 --> 00:27:49.230
"Well, because at the time,

00:27:49.230 --> 00:27:50.530
there were good reasons
why we didn't teach you.

00:27:50.530 --> 00:27:52.740
We thought you were doing --
we were doing the right thing."

00:27:52.740 --> 00:27:55.710
So -- and I think that sometimes
people will give people a hard time

00:27:55.710 --> 00:27:57.570
for not having made
-- and often women --

00:27:57.570 --> 00:27:59.930
like the mother, they're like,
"Well you should've done this mom."

00:27:59.930 --> 00:28:02.330
[Background laughter] and it's not
-- you know, it's not very nice.

00:28:02.330 --> 00:28:04.260 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Yeah, leave aside
the shame and blame, and just --

00:28:04.260 --> 00:28:05.560
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: Exactly.

00:28:05.560 --> 00:28:06.860
"Oh yeah, so I should have
anticipated 30 years ago -- "

00:28:06.860 --> 00:28:08.160
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: And
just -- just learn it.

00:28:08.160 --> 00:28:09.460
Yeah [laughs].

00:28:09.460 --> 00:28:10.760
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria:
That you would've wanted

00:28:10.760 --> 00:28:12.060
to speak this language, thanks.

00:28:12.060 --> 00:28:13.360
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans:
Well, my bad [laughs].

00:28:13.360 --> 00:28:14.660
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria:
Yeah, sorry [laughs].

00:28:14.660 --> 00:28:15.960
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans:
Yeah, maybe next time.

00:28:15.960 --> 00:28:17.260
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Well, I think
song and music is a great way

00:28:17.260 --> 00:28:18.560
into any language culture.

00:28:18.560 --> 00:28:19.860
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: Yeah.

00:28:19.860 --> 00:28:21.160
Yeah. Yeah.

00:28:21.160 --> 00:28:22.460
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: So I think you
guys are doing the right thing.

00:28:22.460 --> 00:28:23.760
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria:
Well hopefully.

00:28:23.760 --> 00:28:25.060
We like it anyway.

00:28:25.060 --> 00:28:26.360
Yeah.

00:28:26.360 --> 00:28:27.660
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Well I'm going
to ask Mikel a few questions,

00:28:27.660 --> 00:28:28.960
and because of the language issue,
I'm going to ask those in French,

00:28:28.960 --> 00:28:31.750
and I'll provide a translation
of course for our video.

00:28:31.750 --> 00:28:33.050
So --

00:28:33.050 --> 00:28:34.350
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Parlons un
peu des traditions populaires des

00:28:34.350 --> 00:28:36.200
Basques dans le pays
Basque lui-même.

00:28:36.200 --> 00:28:47.080 position:56%
Est-ce-qu'il y a beaucoup de gens
qui jouent la musique traditionelle?

00:28:47.080 --> 00:28:55.220
&gt;&gt; Mikel Markez: Oui, il y a.
Nous avons eu beaucoup de gens

00:28:55.220 --> 00:28:58.990
comme...Alan Lomax, no?

00:28:58.990 --> 00:29:01.710
Qui a pris des vieux chansons.

00:29:01.710 --> 00:29:05.050
Et nous étions aux années 60,

00:29:05.050 --> 00:29:09.910
un groupe très intéressant...parce
que, dans la partie Espagnole,

00:29:09.910 --> 00:29:15.880
il y avait un dictatuer,
comme vous a dit Begoña,

00:29:15.880 --> 00:29:19.760
et la langage était interdit.

00:29:19.760 --> 00:29:23.960
Et dans les 60, il est un peu de...

00:29:23.960 --> 00:29:25.260
[Basque language spoken]

00:29:25.260 --> 00:29:26.560
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria:
Yeah research --

00:29:26.560 --> 00:29:27.860
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans: Research.

00:29:27.860 --> 00:29:29.160
&gt;&gt; Mikel Markez: Yes.

00:29:29.160 --> 00:29:30.460
&gt;&gt; Mikel Markez: Il y avait
un groupe qui s'appelle

00:29:30.460 --> 00:29:32.860
"Ez dok amairu."

00:29:32.860 --> 00:29:38.030
Ils sont des chanteurs, qui ont
fait des nouvelles chansons,

00:29:38.030 --> 00:29:39.750
qui ont fait des expérimentations,

00:29:39.750 --> 00:29:46.410
mais qui ont pris des vielles
chansons traditionelles,

00:29:46.410 --> 00:29:56.060
et des romans vieux, et qui les
ont chantées et ont popularisé

00:29:56.060 --> 00:29:57.360
ces chansons.

00:29:57.360 --> 00:30:01.420
Et tout le monde qui nous sommes
venus apres, tous les chanteurs,

00:30:01.420 --> 00:30:08.420
tous les gens culturels, nous avons
apris que c'est très intéressant

00:30:08.420 --> 00:30:12.160
ce que des autres ont fait avant,

00:30:12.160 --> 00:30:16.380
pour faire nous qui a
de raiz, avec la terre.

00:30:16.380 --> 00:30:23.770
C'est pour ça je pense que nous
avons eu un bon école avec ce

00:30:23.770 --> 00:30:27.490
groupe qui est notre premier
réference culturel grand après,

00:30:27.490 --> 00:30:30.530
un peu de le dictateur.

00:30:30.530 --> 00:30:37.360
Et je pense que c'est pour ça que
la culture traditionelle a beaucoup

00:30:37.360 --> 00:30:39.260
de force au Pays Basque.

00:30:39.260 --> 00:30:47.000
Mais il y a une chose que je veux
dire de les chansons vielles et la

00:30:47.000 --> 00:30:51.670
culture populaire ici
dans les États-Unis.

00:30:51.670 --> 00:30:55.660
C'est vrai que nous
avons fait un travail,

00:30:55.660 --> 00:30:59.350
et que des autres ont
fait un travail,

00:30:59.350 --> 00:31:02.350
pour les chansons traditionelles.

00:31:02.350 --> 00:31:12.090
Mais c'est vrai aussi que, comme la
culture au pays Basque est vivant,

00:31:12.090 --> 00:31:18.700
il y a des nouveaux chansons,
il y a des nouveaux verses,

00:31:18.700 --> 00:31:25.560
il y a des nouveaux...des
nouveaux influences du monde.

00:31:25.560 --> 00:31:33.970
Et les choses vieux,
quelque fois, ils sont...

00:31:33.970 --> 00:31:35.270
[mot Basque]

00:31:35.270 --> 00:31:36.570
&gt;&gt; Andréa Bidart: Stabilized.

00:31:36.570 --> 00:31:37.870
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: Fossilized.

00:31:37.870 --> 00:31:39.170
&gt;&gt; Mikel Markez: [Basque word.]

00:31:39.170 --> 00:31:40.470
&gt;&gt; Begoña Echeverria: Fossilized I
think is what he means; fossilized.

00:31:40.470 --> 00:31:41.770
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick:
Je comprends, oui.

00:31:41.770 --> 00:31:43.320
&gt;&gt; Mikel Markez: Et ici,

00:31:43.320 --> 00:31:48.260
nous pouvons écouter
quelques chansons que nous ne

00:31:48.260 --> 00:31:49.650
connaissons pas.

00:31:49.650 --> 00:31:50.950
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Right.

00:31:50.950 --> 00:31:54.250
&gt;&gt; Mikel Markez: Nous sommes, toute
la vie, apprendre des chansons.

00:31:54.250 --> 00:32:00.060
Et nous pensons que nous savions
beaucoup de chansons populaires.

00:32:00.060 --> 00:32:05.890
Mais c'est vrai que nous
venons a Chino, a Boise,

00:32:05.890 --> 00:32:10.100
et il y a un vieux qui
chante une chanson que, oop!

00:32:10.100 --> 00:32:11.760
Je connais pas!

00:32:11.760 --> 00:32:17.940
Et c'est parce-que, pour nous,
c'est past autant important,

00:32:17.940 --> 00:32:21.630
il y a des choses nouvelles.

00:32:21.630 --> 00:32:24.040
Mais ici, c'est gardé!

00:32:24.040 --> 00:32:25.340
&gt;&gt; Cathy Petrissans: That's
all we have, so [laughs] --

00:32:25.340 --> 00:32:32.170
&gt;&gt; Mikel Markez: Dans les lieux
qui la culture Basque et pas fort,

00:32:32.170 --> 00:32:38.180
nous pouvons rencontrer
quelques petits merveilles!

00:32:38.180 --> 00:32:40.450
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Oui,
c'est intéressant!

00:32:40.450 --> 00:32:43.140
&gt;&gt; Mikel Markez: Oui, Oui, Oui,

00:32:43.140 --> 00:32:44.440
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Alors,

00:32:44.440 --> 00:32:46.940
vous composez des chansons
aussi en Basque.

00:32:46.940 --> 00:32:57.150
Est-ce-que vous utilisez
les vers traditionelles?

00:32:57.150 --> 00:32:58.750
&gt;&gt; Mikel Markez: Oui...je
dirais que, moi,

00:32:58.750 --> 00:33:03.410
j'ai trois chemins
qui sont ensembles.

00:33:03.410 --> 00:33:11.120
D'une fois, je fais des chansons,
moi, des paroles et des musiques.

00:33:11.120 --> 00:33:16.500
D'autre fois, je fais des musiques
pour des paroles qui ont fait

00:33:16.500 --> 00:33:17.800
d'autres poètes ou
d'autres écrivains.

00:33:17.800 --> 00:33:21.480
Et la troisieme, c'est
la chanson populaire.

00:33:21.480 --> 00:33:26.680
Tous les disques, je pense,

00:33:26.680 --> 00:33:33.670
j'ai chanté une ou deux chansons
populaires qui nous sont venues par

00:33:33.670 --> 00:33:36.170
la tradition orale.

00:33:36.170 --> 00:33:37.470
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Okay.

00:33:37.470 --> 00:33:44.670
Du temps qui n'avait pas la
possibilite d'enregistrer.

00:33:44.670 --> 00:33:45.970
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Okay.

00:33:45.970 --> 00:33:51.770
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Et de quels
sujets écrivez-vous dans

00:33:51.770 --> 00:33:53.070
vos chansons?

00:33:53.070 --> 00:33:55.380
&gt;&gt; Mikel Markez: Bon, J'écris de
tous les choses qui intéressent

00:33:55.380 --> 00:33:56.880
à l'humain...

00:33:56.880 --> 00:34:00.370
à l'humanité: La
mort, l'amour, le sexe,

00:34:00.370 --> 00:34:06.080
la politique...tous les
choses...les rélations...la vie!

00:34:06.080 --> 00:34:07.420
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Oui.

00:34:07.420 --> 00:34:08.990
&gt;&gt; Mikel Markez: Le vent...tout!

00:34:08.990 --> 00:34:15.360
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Et vous
etes guitariste, aussi.

00:34:15.360 --> 00:34:21.340
&gt;&gt; Mikel Markez: Oui,
je joue la guitare,

00:34:21.340 --> 00:34:24.810
je joue un peu l'accordéon
traditionnel Basque,

00:34:24.810 --> 00:34:26.340
trikitixa, il s'appelle

00:34:26.340 --> 00:34:28.020
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Trikitixa.

00:34:28.020 --> 00:34:29.460
C'est l'accordéon diatonique?

00:34:29.460 --> 00:34:31.090
&gt;&gt; Mikel Markez: L'accordéon
diatonique, oui.

00:34:31.090 --> 00:34:34.150
L'accordéon diatonique
traditionnel Basque.

00:34:34.150 --> 00:34:35.450
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Et la guitare,

00:34:35.450 --> 00:34:39.930
est-ce-que c'est assez
nouvelle dans la musique Basque?

00:34:39.930 --> 00:34:42.640
&gt;&gt; Mikel Markez: Nous avons des
évidences qu'il y avait...bon,

00:34:42.640 --> 00:34:52.100
il y a beaucoup d'années, chanteurs
traditionnels avec la guitare...

00:34:52.100 --> 00:34:53.400
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Mm-hm.

00:34:53.400 --> 00:34:54.700
&gt;&gt; Mikel Markez: ...et
aussi le violon...

00:34:54.700 --> 00:34:56.000
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Oui.

00:34:56.000 --> 00:35:01.370
&gt;&gt; Mikel Markez: ...qui
chantaient des vers vieux,

00:35:01.370 --> 00:35:05.060
des vers...qui content
des histoires comme,

00:35:05.060 --> 00:35:08.940
qu'il y a une personne
qui a tué son pere,

00:35:08.940 --> 00:35:11.180
